1
00:01:09,319 --> 00:01:11,112
Captain!

2
00:01:17,369 --> 00:01:19,412
-Eddie, my briefcase?
-Here.

3
00:01:19,621 --> 00:01:21,331
Hang on to it.

4
00:01:34,803 --> 00:01:38,014
All right, already. Come on, come on.

5
00:01:45,980 --> 00:01:48,441
This way, Mr. Brock.

6
00:02:03,039 --> 00:02:07,877
Mr. Brock, welcome to
the Washington Statler. Your wing--

7
00:02:08,086 --> 00:02:11,840
-I ain't got a whole floor?
-You've got an entire wing.

8
00:02:12,090 --> 00:02:15,760
I don't want one wing.
I want the whole bird.

9
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:20,974
-Your private elevator.
-Private? That's more like it.

10
00:02:21,558 --> 00:02:23,226
-Hello.
-How are you?

11
00:02:23,435 --> 00:02:24,477
Mr. Brock--

12
00:02:24,686 --> 00:02:28,273
I thought you said this
was private. Take off.

13
00:02:29,983 --> 00:02:31,735
You should be satisfied.

14
00:02:33,194 --> 00:02:35,697
The public corridor and elevators--

15
00:02:35,905 --> 00:02:39,993
-West, East and South Suite.
-Which one's mine?

16
00:02:40,201 --> 00:02:43,496
The South Suite.
Each a private apartment.

17
00:02:44,873 --> 00:02:49,753
Sleeping quarters upstairs,
terrace overlooks Washington.

18
00:02:49,961 --> 00:02:52,797
-I'd like to point out--
-It's all right.

19
00:02:53,048 --> 00:02:56,259
I'd like to point out
that this suite--

20
00:03:02,390 --> 00:03:06,353
This suite is usually reserved
for foreign diplomats.

21
00:03:06,561 --> 00:03:10,398
Oh, I almost forgot.
We thought you'd like this.

22
00:03:10,607 --> 00:03:14,152
-Compliments of the management.
-Okay. Don't bother me.

23
00:03:17,822 --> 00:03:19,574
May I?

24
00:03:21,284 --> 00:03:24,996
May I show you the rest
of the accommodations?

25
00:03:34,714 --> 00:03:36,257
Hey, Billie!

26
00:03:39,094 --> 00:03:42,889
-What?
-Not bad, huh?

27
00:03:43,098 --> 00:03:47,602
-It's all right.
-You know what this place costs a day?

28
00:03:47,811 --> 00:03:50,647
Four hundred, you told me.

29
00:04:00,031 --> 00:04:03,827
-Mrs. Brock seems delighted.
-It's not '' Mrs. Brock.''

30
00:04:04,035 --> 00:04:07,038
Ain't no Mrs. Brock except my mother.
She's dead.

31
00:04:07,288 --> 00:04:08,331
I see.

32
00:04:08,540 --> 00:04:12,127
-Now look, don't get nosy.
-Oh, not at all.

33
00:04:12,585 --> 00:04:18,383
She's a fiancÃ©e. Mine, in fact.
Eddie, take care of him.

34
00:04:19,300 --> 00:04:20,719
Pardon me, sir.

35
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:24,931
-Thank you, Mr. Brock.
-Okay. Don't bother me.

36
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:28,184
How's the monarch of all he surveys?

37
00:04:28,393 --> 00:04:31,396
-You plastered again?
-Still. Welcome.

38
00:04:31,646 --> 00:04:33,606
I got things that can't wait.

39
00:04:33,815 --> 00:04:36,985
-I got this ticket to get fixed.
-What about?

40
00:04:37,193 --> 00:04:40,113
Some louse, just as we blew into town.

41
00:04:40,363 --> 00:04:44,325
-I'm a lawyer, I don't own the law.
-What'd I do?

42
00:04:44,576 --> 00:04:46,786
I'll see what I can manage.

43
00:04:47,245 --> 00:04:49,748
-How'd we do?
-May cost a shade more.

44
00:04:49,998 --> 00:04:51,624
-How much?
-It's negligible.

45
00:04:51,833 --> 00:04:54,085
-Why more?
-Supply and demand, Harry.

46
00:04:54,336 --> 00:04:57,422
Crooks are rare in these parts.
Don't worry.

47
00:04:57,630 --> 00:05:00,383
Don't worry?
This stuff ain't deductible.

48
00:05:00,592 --> 00:05:04,763
I'm not so sure.
'' ltem: One bribe, $80,000.''

49
00:05:04,971 --> 00:05:07,766
Eighty! You're very handy
with my dough!

50
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:13,480
Fellow's coming up here any minute
to interview you. Paul Verrall.

51
00:05:13,688 --> 00:05:15,982
Freelance snoop. Political stuff.

52
00:05:16,191 --> 00:05:19,569
I don't wanna talk to no writer.
Eddie!

53
00:05:19,778 --> 00:05:22,197
-You better talk to this one.
-Why?

54
00:05:22,405 --> 00:05:27,827
He's one to look out for.
Take him in, then he won't go poking.

55
00:05:28,036 --> 00:05:30,955
What's so important?

56
00:05:31,456 --> 00:05:33,708
What we're after is important.

57
00:05:33,958 --> 00:05:37,879
Listen, to get by in this town
takes power. You got some.

58
00:05:38,088 --> 00:05:40,006
Takes money. You got plenty.

59
00:05:40,215 --> 00:05:43,927
But above all, it takes
judgement and intelligence.

60
00:05:44,135 --> 00:05:47,472
That's why you pay me
1 00,000 a year.

61
00:05:48,098 --> 00:05:53,103
-What's all the excitement?
-Just making it clear where I fit in.

62
00:05:53,311 --> 00:05:56,231
-Eddie, get me a shave up here.
-Right.

63
00:05:56,439 --> 00:05:57,691
-Harry.
-What?

64
00:05:57,941 --> 00:05:58,983
Barber shop!

65
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:02,821
Tell Billie to wear something plain
for the congressman.

66
00:06:03,071 --> 00:06:05,824
Tell her yourself. You ain't pregnant.

67
00:06:06,074 --> 00:06:08,743
Send up a barber
and a manicure right now.

68
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:12,414
Harry Brock! That's right.
Okay, make it snappy.

69
00:06:12,622 --> 00:06:15,250
-And a shine!
-And a shine! Be right up.

70
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:20,755
Look, don't you worry about Billie.
One thing, she knows how to dress.

71
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:22,590
Probably Verrall.

72
00:06:24,634 --> 00:06:26,386
-Hello, Paul.
-Hello, Jim.

73
00:06:26,636 --> 00:06:28,179
Harry Brock, Paul Verrall.

74
00:06:28,430 --> 00:06:30,181
-How do you do?
-How are you?

75
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:33,893
-Ain't I seen you before?
-I'll leave you.

76
00:06:34,102 --> 00:06:35,770
What'll you drink?

77
00:06:35,979 --> 00:06:38,648
-Scotch, if you got it.
-lf I got it? Eddie.

78
00:06:38,857 --> 00:06:40,692
Where do you think you are?

79
00:06:40,942 --> 00:06:43,611
Where you been?
Get him a Scotch and--

80
00:06:43,862 --> 00:06:45,071
-Soda?
-Water.

81
00:06:45,321 --> 00:06:49,451
-Rye ginger ale for you?
-Right. He knows.

82
00:06:49,659 --> 00:06:53,872
Worked for me many years.
He's my cousin. He knows me.

83
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:56,666
-Right.
-Maybe I'll interview Eddie.

84
00:06:56,875 --> 00:07:00,920
Pretty good. Maybe you
got something there. Sit down.

85
00:07:01,129 --> 00:07:04,799
What's it gonna be, pal?
A plug or a pan?

86
00:07:05,008 --> 00:07:07,594
I know how to talk
if I know your angle.

87
00:07:07,844 --> 00:07:10,388
-No angle, just facts.
-A pan?

88
00:07:10,597 --> 00:07:13,224
-Not exactly.
-Write whatever you want.

89
00:07:13,475 --> 00:07:15,185
Come up. I wanna get shaved.

90
00:07:15,477 --> 00:07:20,231
Nobody can hurt me.
I'm only talking because Jim asked me.

91
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:24,444
Pay him 1 00 grand for advice,
I'm a sucker not to take it.

92
00:07:24,694 --> 00:07:27,947
-That's right.
-Butt out, will you?

93
00:07:28,823 --> 00:07:31,576
Devery likes it
when I get wrote about.

94
00:07:31,826 --> 00:07:35,622
-What do you wanna know?
-How much money you got?

95
00:07:35,830 --> 00:07:36,873
What?

96
00:07:37,082 --> 00:07:40,043
-How much money?
-What am l, an accountant?

97
00:07:40,293 --> 00:07:42,212
-You don't know?
-Not exactly.

98
00:07:42,462 --> 00:07:44,631
-Fifty million?
-I don't know.

99
00:07:44,881 --> 00:07:46,299
-Ten million?
-Maybe.

100
00:07:46,549 --> 00:07:48,009
-One million?
-More.

101
00:07:48,259 --> 00:07:50,011
-How much more?
-Plenty.

102
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:55,266
-I made every nickel of it.
-Nice work.

103
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:59,270
You're gonna give me the business.
That's all right.

104
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:02,565
-You got me all--
-Tell how I'm a roughneck.

105
00:08:02,816 --> 00:08:05,276
Everybody's scared.
For me, that's good.

106
00:08:05,443 --> 00:08:06,986
Well, not everybody.

107
00:08:07,153 --> 00:08:11,366
Enough. You can't hurt me.
All you can do is build me up.

108
00:08:11,616 --> 00:08:15,120
-Hey, Eddie. Have a drink.
-No, thanks, really.

109
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:18,832
Do what I tell you.
Who pays you around here?

110
00:08:20,208 --> 00:08:24,462
At home, he shaves me.
I got my own barber chair, right?

111
00:08:24,671 --> 00:08:26,131
That's right.

112
00:08:27,090 --> 00:08:30,760
-Go ahead, pal. lnterview me.
-Where were you born?

113
00:08:30,969 --> 00:08:36,224
Plainfield, New Jersey. 1 907. I went
to work when I was 1 2 years old.

114
00:08:36,433 --> 00:08:41,146
I been working ever since.
My first job was a paper route.

115
00:08:41,396 --> 00:08:43,898
I bought a kid out with a swift kick.

116
00:08:44,107 --> 00:08:46,443
And you've been
working ever since.

117
00:08:46,651 --> 00:08:51,573
Tell you how I'm top man in my racket.
Been in it 25 years.

118
00:08:51,781 --> 00:08:55,160
-Steel.
-Not steel, junk.

119
00:08:55,410 --> 00:08:59,622
-And I ain't ashamed to admit it.
-All right.

120
00:08:59,831 --> 00:09:02,792
Here's some advice:
Never bull a bull artist.

121
00:09:03,001 --> 00:09:06,212
I can sling it with the best of them.

122
00:09:06,463 --> 00:09:10,842
-For 25 years, you say?
-Yeah. I'm a kid with a paper route.

123
00:09:11,051 --> 00:09:14,804
I got a wagon. Going home,
I pick up junk in alleys.

124
00:09:15,013 --> 00:09:18,266
I'm not the only one.
Other kids do it too.

125
00:09:18,475 --> 00:09:21,895
Difference is, they keep it.
Not me. I sell it.

126
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:26,274
I'm making eight dollars in junk
and three from papers.

127
00:09:26,524 --> 00:09:30,653
I see which is the right racket.
I'm a kid, but I see that.

128
00:09:30,904 --> 00:09:34,282
Soon the guy I sell to
is handing me 20 a week.

129
00:09:34,741 --> 00:09:38,745
Then he turns around,
offers me a job for 1 0. Dumb jerk.

130
00:09:38,995 --> 00:09:42,082
I'd sell him his own stuff
and he never knew.

131
00:09:42,332 --> 00:09:44,417
-How do you mean?
-Look....

132
00:09:44,626 --> 00:09:48,213
In the night,
I drag it out, I load it up.

133
00:09:48,421 --> 00:09:51,633
In the morning I go in
the front and collect.

134
00:09:51,883 --> 00:09:54,803
-Twelve years old?
-Something like that.

135
00:09:55,178 --> 00:09:57,806
-Pretty soon you own the yard.
-Right.

136
00:09:58,014 --> 00:10:01,518
The jerk works for me now.
Know who else does?

137
00:10:01,726 --> 00:10:07,065
The kid whose paper route I swiped.
I figure I owe him.

138
00:10:08,233 --> 00:10:11,236
Good last few years
for the junk business.

139
00:10:11,444 --> 00:10:16,032
-I ain't kicking.
-Do you anticipate any decline now?

140
00:10:16,366 --> 00:10:19,494
-Talk plain.
-Is it still going to be good?

141
00:10:19,703 --> 00:10:21,287
-We'll make it good.
-Who?

142
00:10:21,496 --> 00:10:23,081
-Me, that's who.
-I see.

143
00:10:23,289 --> 00:10:25,750
-Fancy talk don't go with me.
-Come in.

144
00:10:26,334 --> 00:10:28,753
-Good evening.
-Hello.

145
00:10:29,462 --> 00:10:32,173
-I'll get out--
-No, don't go. I like you.

146
00:10:32,424 --> 00:10:36,136
Play your cards right,
I'll put you on the payroll.

147
00:10:36,386 --> 00:10:41,474
Once over light, no talk.
I get a manicure every day.

148
00:10:42,517 --> 00:10:45,020
Over there someplace.

149
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:48,982
Okay, fellow, go ahead.

150
00:10:49,190 --> 00:10:52,360
I wonder what you're doing
in Washington.

151
00:10:52,569 --> 00:10:55,739
What are you, a wonder boy?
Not so tight.

152
00:10:55,989 --> 00:10:58,867
Sightseeing, that's what I'm doing.

153
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:01,786
Some talk you've come
to find out--

154
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:04,914
So far I've been nice to you.
Don't pump me.

155
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:09,669
How's it going? How are you getting
on with King Junk?

156
00:11:09,878 --> 00:11:13,798
He was born in New Jersey.
Sure is a tough man to dig.

157
00:11:14,007 --> 00:11:17,260
I can't believe that.
He loves to talk. Billie!

158
00:11:17,469 --> 00:11:19,763
This is Paul Verrall.
Billie Dawn.

159
00:11:20,013 --> 00:11:21,056
How do you do?

160
00:11:23,266 --> 00:11:25,393
-Wait.
-What's the matter?

161
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:28,772
Where you going? Put it back!

162
00:11:29,147 --> 00:11:31,316
-I just wanted--
-Put it back!

163
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:33,068
-Why--?
-Because I say.

164
00:11:33,318 --> 00:11:36,196
Somebody's coming.
I don't want you stinking.

165
00:11:36,446 --> 00:11:41,326
-Can't I just--?
-Go change. Don't give me no trouble!

166
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:44,037
Do what I'm telling you!

167
00:11:56,216 --> 00:11:59,886
Barber, what'll you take
to cut his throat?

168
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:02,597
Some jokes I don't like.

169
00:12:02,806 --> 00:12:06,351
-Don't get excited.
-Don't tell me what to do!

170
00:12:07,519 --> 00:12:11,648
-Just a joke, Harry.
-That's all. I said beat it.

171
00:12:11,898 --> 00:12:13,316
Eddie, take care of them.

172
00:12:13,566 --> 00:12:15,819
-I'll be going too.
-No, don't.

173
00:12:16,027 --> 00:12:18,113
You're the only friend
I got left.

174
00:12:18,363 --> 00:12:22,534
I live around the corner.
lf anybody beats you, scream.

175
00:12:22,742 --> 00:12:24,160
I'll come running.

176
00:12:24,411 --> 00:12:27,038
-Goodbye, Jim. Thanks.
-Goodbye.

177
00:12:28,957 --> 00:12:31,251
I need Billie's signature.

178
00:12:31,459 --> 00:12:34,713
Sure. Billie!

179
00:12:36,047 --> 00:12:39,759
-You sore?
-Not sore, Harry.

180
00:12:40,593 --> 00:12:43,513
-You look funny.
-I know.

181
00:12:44,389 --> 00:12:48,643
-You want an aspirin?
-No, no, I'm fine.

182
00:12:49,144 --> 00:12:52,272
Considering I've been dead
for 1 6 years...

183
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:55,358
...I'm in remarkable health.

184
00:13:02,157 --> 00:13:04,993
-Billie!
-What?

185
00:13:05,201 --> 00:13:07,037
Billie!

186
00:13:09,414 --> 00:13:12,500
-What?
-Come over here right away!

187
00:13:12,876 --> 00:13:15,837
Honey, would you please
fix the safety catch?

188
00:13:16,046 --> 00:13:19,215
-He sure got good lungs.
-Yeah. Thanks.

189
00:13:19,466 --> 00:13:23,136
There's a shortcut through
the service. This way.

190
00:13:27,932 --> 00:13:31,269
-That's the door, honey.
-Thanks, honey.

191
00:13:39,694 --> 00:13:42,072
Sometime I don't understand you.

192
00:13:42,280 --> 00:13:44,991
-Sometime?
-What do you want?

193
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,242
Jim.

194
00:13:46,451 --> 00:13:49,245
Few things I want you to sign, honey.

195
00:13:49,454 --> 00:13:53,958
-That's all I do around here.
-Too bad about you.

196
00:13:54,167 --> 00:13:56,961
-When's this congressman coming?
-Anytime.

197
00:13:57,212 --> 00:13:59,255
I better get fixed up, huh?

198
00:13:59,506 --> 00:14:02,133
-She look all right?
-Look who's talking.

199
00:14:02,342 --> 00:14:06,471
You tell me. I don't wanna start off
on no left foot.

200
00:14:09,391 --> 00:14:11,142
What got into him?

201
00:14:11,351 --> 00:14:14,270
Nothing. Wants to make
a good impression.

202
00:14:14,521 --> 00:14:16,106
So let him.

203
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:21,152
Two places on this one, please.

204
00:14:21,361 --> 00:14:24,489
What happened to all that stuff
I signed last week?

205
00:14:24,739 --> 00:14:26,324
All used up.

206
00:14:27,158 --> 00:14:30,036
I must've signed
about a million of these.

207
00:14:30,245 --> 00:14:32,580
What you get as corporate officer.

208
00:14:32,789 --> 00:14:35,917
I am? What do you know?

209
00:14:36,835 --> 00:14:39,212
Come a long way from the chorus.

210
00:14:39,421 --> 00:14:42,632
I wasn't only in the chorus.
I spoke lines.

211
00:14:42,882 --> 00:14:45,301
-Really?
-Of course.

212
00:14:46,344 --> 00:14:49,097
-How many?
-How many what?

213
00:14:49,305 --> 00:14:51,850
-Lines did you speak?
-Five.

214
00:14:52,642 --> 00:14:55,145
-I never knew that.
-Ask anybody.

215
00:14:55,353 --> 00:14:56,980
I believe you.

216
00:14:58,064 --> 00:15:01,818
I could've been a star
if I'd have stuck to it.

217
00:15:02,027 --> 00:15:06,197
-Why didn't you?
-Harry didn't want me in the show.

218
00:15:06,448 --> 00:15:10,326
He didn't wanna share me
with the general public.

219
00:15:10,535 --> 00:15:11,953
I see.

220
00:15:14,789 --> 00:15:17,834
Harry's changed. Don't you think so?

221
00:15:18,126 --> 00:15:21,755
-How?
-He used to be more satisfied.

222
00:15:21,963 --> 00:15:24,341
Now he's always
running around like this.

223
00:15:24,591 --> 00:15:27,260
What'd he have to come
to Washington for?

224
00:15:27,510 --> 00:15:31,431
-Long story.
-Well, don't tell it to me.

225
00:15:31,681 --> 00:15:36,436
-I just wish he'd settle down.
-He's ambitious.

226
00:15:36,644 --> 00:15:39,898
He talks all the time now.
He never used to.

227
00:15:40,106 --> 00:15:45,195
Now he always tells me how
he's gonna be bigger, run everything.

228
00:15:45,445 --> 00:15:50,950
-He may, at that.
-I don't care one way or the other.

229
00:15:52,869 --> 00:15:55,663
-Take it easy.
-Now don't you start!

230
00:15:55,872 --> 00:15:58,375
Better to drink after they're gone.

231
00:15:58,583 --> 00:16:00,960
-This congressman?
-And Mrs. Hedges.

232
00:16:01,169 --> 00:16:04,130
-This fella works for him.
-In a way.

233
00:16:04,339 --> 00:16:06,841
So what's he putting it on for?

234
00:16:07,884 --> 00:16:10,011
Just be nice. No rough language.

235
00:16:10,261 --> 00:16:13,556
-I won't open my mush.
-I didn't mean that.

236
00:16:13,807 --> 00:16:18,269
I don't have to be down here.
I could go back to my place.

237
00:16:18,478 --> 00:16:20,980
In fact, I think I will.

238
00:16:21,189 --> 00:16:25,777
-I tell you, Harry wouldn't like it.
-All right, all right!

239
00:16:33,618 --> 00:16:37,247
How are you, Norval?
Haven't seen you in ages, Anna.

240
00:16:37,497 --> 00:16:38,998
-You haven't.
-Come in.

241
00:16:39,249 --> 00:16:44,004
You remember this little lady.
She used to be Billie Dawn.

242
00:16:44,254 --> 00:16:46,297
Oh, yes. Yes, indeed.

243
00:16:46,548 --> 00:16:49,217
This is Mr. Hedges
I've told you about.

244
00:16:49,426 --> 00:16:51,094
-How do you do?
-How do you do?

245
00:16:51,344 --> 00:16:54,848
-And this is Mrs. Hedges.
-Glad to meet you.

246
00:16:55,056 --> 00:16:57,058
Glad to meet you.

247
00:17:02,814 --> 00:17:06,026
-How about the terrace?
-That'd be nice.

248
00:17:06,234 --> 00:17:07,360
-A drink?
-Love one.

249
00:17:07,610 --> 00:17:09,446
-Sounds all right.
-Scotch?

250
00:17:09,696 --> 00:17:12,115
-Scotch all around, Eddie.
-Right.

251
00:17:18,163 --> 00:17:19,247
He's awfully tired.

252
00:17:19,497 --> 00:17:24,377
-Stand over a hot resolution all day?
-Just about.

253
00:17:35,764 --> 00:17:38,808
How do you like Washington,
Mrs. Brock?

254
00:17:46,191 --> 00:17:51,112
-I haven't seen it yet.
-This is the first time you've been?

255
00:17:51,321 --> 00:17:55,075
That's what I mean.
I never went on the road.

256
00:17:55,283 --> 00:17:59,287
Well, we must show you around.
Beautiful city.

257
00:17:59,537 --> 00:18:03,249
Too bad the Supreme Court
isn't in session.

258
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:05,085
What is it?

259
00:18:10,256 --> 00:18:12,801
Lots of people'd
like to know that.

260
00:18:13,009 --> 00:18:15,470
-Hello.
-Mr. Hedges, Harry Brock.

261
00:18:15,679 --> 00:18:17,722
It's about time we got together.

262
00:18:17,931 --> 00:18:20,725
Mrs. Hedges, I'm happy to meet you.

263
00:18:20,934 --> 00:18:23,853
-Thank you.
-Sit down. Congressman.

264
00:18:30,819 --> 00:18:33,488
-Have a good trip?
-I come in my car.

265
00:18:33,738 --> 00:18:38,076
Stopped in Baltimore.
I got a junkyard there, second one.

266
00:18:38,326 --> 00:18:41,579
-Before, I only had one.
-How many do you have?

267
00:18:41,788 --> 00:18:43,957
I couldn't answer that, baby.

268
00:18:45,750 --> 00:18:47,877
-Excuse me.
-That's all right.

269
00:18:48,128 --> 00:18:52,424
I don't know why I like Baltimore.
I get a feeling from it.

270
00:18:52,632 --> 00:18:55,385
-Sentimental.
-Yes, I'm sentimental.

271
00:18:55,593 --> 00:18:59,264
I think we're all a bit sentimental.

272
00:18:59,806 --> 00:19:03,435
Well, it's a free country.

273
00:19:08,940 --> 00:19:13,278
-Do you play bridge, Mrs. Brock?
-No, only gin.

274
00:19:13,778 --> 00:19:15,739
-I beg your pardon?
-Gin rummy.

275
00:19:15,947 --> 00:19:17,866
Oh, yes, of course.

276
00:19:18,116 --> 00:19:22,495
I was going to ask you to join us.
A few of the girls meet.

277
00:19:22,704 --> 00:19:25,248
I don't play bridge.

278
00:19:25,498 --> 00:19:28,501
-You could learn!
-I don't think so.

279
00:19:28,918 --> 00:19:33,256
She couldn't play till I learned her.
Now she beats my brains out.

280
00:19:35,050 --> 00:19:38,094
How're you fixed for time tomorrow?

281
00:19:38,303 --> 00:19:40,805
-Ten o'clock?
-Pretty early for me.

282
00:19:41,014 --> 00:19:43,058
I'll say.

283
00:19:44,851 --> 00:19:46,936
-Eleven?
-Okay.

284
00:19:47,354 --> 00:19:50,982
-I can drop by here.
-Sure, it's on your way.

285
00:19:51,191 --> 00:19:55,362
We can discuss the operation
and get a head start.

286
00:19:58,823 --> 00:20:02,452
Wanna wash your hands
or anything, honey?

287
00:20:03,453 --> 00:20:05,246
<i>NO, thank yOu.</i>

288
00:20:07,957 --> 00:20:10,919
I hope you're free
for Friday night dinner.

289
00:20:11,127 --> 00:20:14,589
-People I want Harry to meet.
-Who wanna meet him.

290
00:20:14,798 --> 00:20:19,010
-Thank you for everything, Mr. Brock.
-Call me Harry.

291
00:20:19,260 --> 00:20:22,555
I haven't written you....
You understand.

292
00:20:22,764 --> 00:20:25,475
You know I'm interested
in scrap iron.

293
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:29,646
I wanna sell it and not get stuck
with falling prices.

294
00:20:29,896 --> 00:20:34,025
-I have a copy--
-Boil it down and give it to me.

295
00:20:34,234 --> 00:20:38,738
I didn't come here to do paperwork.
The way I work is this:

296
00:20:38,947 --> 00:20:41,825
Get the other guy
before he gets you.

297
00:20:43,451 --> 00:20:48,415
I got in mind a worldwide
operating combo. Enough for everybody.

298
00:20:48,623 --> 00:20:53,128
Up till now, everybody's lined up
and understands everybody.

299
00:20:53,336 --> 00:20:57,090
-I wanna move.
-You understand that legislation--

300
00:20:57,298 --> 00:21:02,595
That's a lot of hot air.
I ain't talking about peanuts....

301
00:21:03,847 --> 00:21:06,933
Give them enough rope. I've said so.

302
00:21:11,896 --> 00:21:14,524
The trouble with these do-gooders is--

303
00:21:14,733 --> 00:21:18,987
They never seem to know when to stop.
I've said--

304
00:21:20,530 --> 00:21:24,242
We can do this.
It's up to you to find out how.

305
00:21:24,492 --> 00:21:26,995
One amendment, for example...

306
00:21:27,245 --> 00:21:31,583
...guarantees government support
of scrap iron price levels.

307
00:21:31,833 --> 00:21:33,626
We want to get it through.

308
00:21:33,835 --> 00:21:38,131
See that you do. I'm here
to see that I get what I paid for.

309
00:21:38,381 --> 00:21:41,593
-How do things look to you?
-Generally?

310
00:21:41,801 --> 00:21:47,432
This country has to decide if
the people will run the government...

311
00:21:47,640 --> 00:21:49,976
...or the other way around.

312
00:21:50,185 --> 00:21:51,811
That's sound thinking.

313
00:21:52,062 --> 00:21:53,855
-Thank you.
-Worthy of Holmes.

314
00:21:54,064 --> 00:21:55,774
Great man, Holmes.

315
00:21:56,024 --> 00:21:59,319
-My personal god.
-Who?

316
00:21:59,778 --> 00:22:03,615
-Oliver Wendell Holmes.
-A wonderful man.

317
00:22:04,032 --> 00:22:06,201
He gonna be here Friday night?

318
00:22:06,451 --> 00:22:09,120
-I don't think so.
-Too bad.

319
00:22:09,329 --> 00:22:11,873
-We mustn't keep you.
-We mustn't.

320
00:22:12,082 --> 00:22:14,125
-Good night.
-Good night.

321
00:22:14,376 --> 00:22:17,629
-Good night. See you tomorrow.
-That's right.

322
00:22:17,837 --> 00:22:20,965
-Good night, Anna.
-Thank you so much.

323
00:22:21,174 --> 00:22:25,136
Wait a while. I'll give you
something to thank me for.

324
00:22:26,179 --> 00:22:27,681
Good night, all.

325
00:22:46,449 --> 00:22:47,951
Drips.

326
00:22:48,159 --> 00:22:50,412
-They're drips.
-Who are you to say?

327
00:22:50,620 --> 00:22:53,748
-I'm myself.
-Nobody asked you. Shut up.

328
00:22:53,998 --> 00:22:57,752
-Pardon me for living.
-Get lost.

329
00:22:58,003 --> 00:23:00,797
-Not yet.
-Get lost, I told you.

330
00:23:14,227 --> 00:23:17,313
-She'll be in the way.
-What are you gonna do?

331
00:23:17,564 --> 00:23:20,650
-I'd like to give her the brush.
-Complicated.

332
00:23:20,859 --> 00:23:24,154
-I know.
-She owns more of you than you do.

333
00:23:24,362 --> 00:23:29,117
She's gonna louse me up down the line.
Dumb broad.

334
00:23:29,534 --> 00:23:30,869
You may be right.

335
00:23:31,119 --> 00:23:33,955
-Listen, Harry. Send her home.
-No.

336
00:23:34,164 --> 00:23:35,707
Why not?

337
00:23:38,501 --> 00:23:41,921
-I'm nuts for her.
-Can't have your cake and eat it.

338
00:23:42,130 --> 00:23:43,423
Just a saying.

339
00:23:43,631 --> 00:23:47,052
-That don't make any sense.
-All right.

340
00:23:50,638 --> 00:23:54,768
-What's cake got to do with it?
-Nothing, Harry.

341
00:23:54,976 --> 00:23:57,979
-Must be a way to smarten her up.
-I guess so.

342
00:23:58,229 --> 00:24:00,899
-Some kind of school?
-I doubt that.

343
00:24:01,066 --> 00:24:02,317
Then what?

344
00:24:02,484 --> 00:24:06,112
We might find someone
to smooth the rough edges.

345
00:24:06,321 --> 00:24:08,990
-How?
-Let me think about it.

346
00:24:10,075 --> 00:24:14,037
I want you to think about something.
About marrying her.

347
00:24:14,245 --> 00:24:16,706
Why marriage all of a sudden?

348
00:24:16,915 --> 00:24:20,460
A wife couldn't testify
against her husband.

349
00:24:20,669 --> 00:24:24,172
You've been engaged for seven years.
Why wait?

350
00:24:24,381 --> 00:24:26,174
I didn't wanna be rushed.

351
00:24:26,383 --> 00:24:29,928
We get married,
she'll think she's got it coming.

352
00:24:30,136 --> 00:24:32,305
-She's different.
-A broad's a broad.

353
00:24:32,514 --> 00:24:35,016
-You'll be sorry.
-I'll let you know.

354
00:24:35,266 --> 00:24:37,977
We still gotta do something about her.

355
00:24:38,186 --> 00:24:42,774
She opens her kisser,
something wrong come out. Talk to her.

356
00:24:42,982 --> 00:24:45,235
-Take more than a talk.
-Then what?

357
00:24:45,443 --> 00:24:48,571
It's not easy to make a person over.

358
00:24:48,780 --> 00:24:52,826
Wait. That interview guy.
He's a smart cookie.

359
00:24:53,034 --> 00:24:54,285
Paul Verrall.

360
00:24:54,494 --> 00:24:56,996
He knows this town. He's classy.

361
00:24:57,247 --> 00:24:59,082
-But he won't do it.
-Why?

362
00:24:59,332 --> 00:25:02,585
-I'll pay him what he wants.
-I don't think so.

363
00:25:02,794 --> 00:25:05,005
I bet you. What's his number?

364
00:25:05,255 --> 00:25:09,259
-I'm not sure--
-What's his number? Come on.

365
00:25:11,011 --> 00:25:13,304
-You ate already?
-Yeah.

366
00:25:13,722 --> 00:25:15,348
-Piece of pie?
-No.

367
00:25:15,598 --> 00:25:18,226
-Sit. How about a drink?
-No, thanks.

368
00:25:24,983 --> 00:25:26,609
Okay, pal.

369
00:25:26,860 --> 00:25:29,904
-I wanna ask you something.
-Sure.

370
00:25:30,113 --> 00:25:33,033
-How much you make?
-Am I an accountant?

371
00:25:33,241 --> 00:25:36,411
-I love this guy. Your name again?
-Verrall.

372
00:25:36,661 --> 00:25:38,496
-Your regular name.
-Paul.

373
00:25:38,705 --> 00:25:43,918
I got a friend, a good kid--
Maybe you seen her around. Billie?

374
00:25:44,169 --> 00:25:46,796
She's a little on the stupid side.

375
00:25:47,005 --> 00:25:49,341
I got her out of the chorus.

376
00:25:49,549 --> 00:25:54,471
She'll be unhappy here,
never been with such kind of people.

377
00:25:54,679 --> 00:25:56,473
-Know what I mean?
-I don't.

378
00:25:56,723 --> 00:26:00,143
-You could help her out. Me too.
-How?

379
00:26:00,352 --> 00:26:05,190
Explain things to her in your
spare time. What do you say?

380
00:26:05,440 --> 00:26:10,028
-I don't think I could handle it.
-Mean an awful lot to me.

381
00:26:10,987 --> 00:26:13,782
I'll give you 200 bucks a week.

382
00:26:16,659 --> 00:26:19,329
-I'll do it.
-I love this guy.

383
00:26:19,537 --> 00:26:21,247
-When do I start?
-Now.

384
00:26:21,456 --> 00:26:26,711
Come with me and I'll introduce you.
You can take it from there.

385
00:26:32,425 --> 00:26:33,718
Billie!

386
00:26:34,094 --> 00:26:37,764
-What?!
-Come down here a minute. Come on in.

387
00:26:38,014 --> 00:26:40,684
She's a nice kid.
You're gonna like her.

388
00:26:42,143 --> 00:26:46,523
-I'm getting dressed.
-He's a friend of the family.

389
00:26:46,731 --> 00:26:49,234
Come on, I'm telling you!

390
00:26:53,154 --> 00:26:55,115
-This is Paul Verrall.
-I know.

391
00:26:55,365 --> 00:26:56,991
He wants to talk to you.

392
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:59,244
-What about?
-You'll find out.

393
00:26:59,452 --> 00:27:03,832
Jim and I got work to do.
I'll have to leave you two.

394
00:27:16,720 --> 00:27:19,889
Your friend, Mr. Brock, has an idea.

395
00:27:20,140 --> 00:27:23,268
He'd like us to spend
a little time together.

396
00:27:23,518 --> 00:27:25,145
You and me, that is.

397
00:27:25,395 --> 00:27:27,439
-You don't say.
-Yes.

398
00:27:27,647 --> 00:27:30,984
-What are you, a gigolo?
-Not exactly.

399
00:27:31,192 --> 00:27:34,738
-So what's the idea?
-Well, it's nothing special.

400
00:27:34,946 --> 00:27:39,659
He'd like me to put you wise
to a few things, show you the ropes.

401
00:27:39,868 --> 00:27:42,412
-Answer any questions.
-I got none.

402
00:27:42,620 --> 00:27:45,749
-I'll give you some.
-Thanks.

403
00:27:46,916 --> 00:27:50,378
It might be fun for you.
There's a lot to see here.

404
00:27:50,587 --> 00:27:52,672
I'd be glad to show you around.

405
00:27:52,922 --> 00:27:55,175
-You know the Supreme Court?
-Yes.

406
00:27:55,383 --> 00:27:58,094
-I'd like to take that in.
-Fine.

407
00:27:58,345 --> 00:28:00,597
-We're on, then?
-How you mean?

408
00:28:00,764 --> 00:28:02,015
The arrangement.

409
00:28:02,182 --> 00:28:06,019
-I don't mind. Got nothing to do.
-Good.

410
00:28:06,269 --> 00:28:09,147
-What's he paying you?
-Two hundred.

411
00:28:09,397 --> 00:28:12,233
You could've got more.
He's got plenty.

412
00:28:12,442 --> 00:28:14,694
Oh, I'd have done it for free.

413
00:28:14,903 --> 00:28:16,363
-I would.
-Why?

414
00:28:16,571 --> 00:28:19,532
This isn't work. I like it.

415
00:28:19,783 --> 00:28:22,410
-He thinks I'm too stupid, huh?
-No.

416
00:28:22,619 --> 00:28:25,205
He's right. I'm stupid and I like it.

417
00:28:25,872 --> 00:28:27,248
-You do?
-Sure.

418
00:28:27,457 --> 00:28:31,836
I got everything I want.
Two mink coats, everything.

419
00:28:32,045 --> 00:28:35,006
lf there's something I want, I ask.

420
00:28:35,215 --> 00:28:37,884
And if he don't act friendly...

421
00:28:39,719 --> 00:28:42,055
...I don't act friendly.

422
00:28:43,181 --> 00:28:47,227
As long as I know how to get
what I want, that's all.

423
00:28:47,435 --> 00:28:50,563
-As long as you know what you want.
-Sure.

424
00:28:50,772 --> 00:28:54,526
-What?
-As long as you know what you want.

425
00:28:54,776 --> 00:28:58,655
-Are you trying to mix me up?
-Well, no.

426
00:29:03,368 --> 00:29:06,413
-I'll tell you what I would like.
-Yes?

427
00:29:06,621 --> 00:29:10,083
-I'd like to learn how to talk good.
-All right.

428
00:29:10,417 --> 00:29:12,877
-Is it hard?
-I don't think so.

429
00:29:13,086 --> 00:29:14,963
What do I have to do?

430
00:29:15,171 --> 00:29:18,550
I might give you
a few books to start with.

431
00:29:18,758 --> 00:29:22,345
Every now and then I'll correct you.

432
00:29:22,595 --> 00:29:25,265
-Go ahead.
-Well, that is, when I know.

433
00:29:25,473 --> 00:29:28,184
-I don't talk so good myself.
-You'll do.

434
00:29:28,393 --> 00:29:31,396
-Good.
-I never say ''ain't.'' Did you notice?

435
00:29:31,604 --> 00:29:34,315
-Oh, I do.
-I'll correct you then.

436
00:29:34,899 --> 00:29:38,153
-Do that.
-Since I was small I never say it.

437
00:29:38,403 --> 00:29:41,031
Our teacher used to slug you
if you did.

438
00:29:41,239 --> 00:29:43,116
-Did what?
-Said ''ain't.''

439
00:29:43,324 --> 00:29:46,911
-I got out of the habit.
-Was it worth the slugging?

440
00:29:47,162 --> 00:29:48,288
Oh, not hard.

441
00:29:48,496 --> 00:29:52,167
There's too much slugging.
I don't believe in it.

442
00:29:52,417 --> 00:29:54,836
-I don't believe in it either.
-Good.

443
00:29:55,045 --> 00:29:57,797
-I learn fast.
-You're great, Miss Dawn.

444
00:29:58,048 --> 00:30:01,092
-Billie.
-Billie. An odd name, isn't it?

445
00:30:01,301 --> 00:30:03,762
Half the kids I know are named it.

446
00:30:03,970 --> 00:30:07,932
-Anyway, it isn't my real name.
-Oh? What is?

447
00:30:08,141 --> 00:30:10,769
Holy cats. Emma.

448
00:30:11,186 --> 00:30:14,856
-What's the matter?
-Do I look to you like an Emma?

449
00:30:15,273 --> 00:30:18,443
No. You don't look
like a Billie either.

450
00:30:19,110 --> 00:30:20,528
What do I look like?

451
00:30:20,779 --> 00:30:22,989
-To me?
-Yeah, you.

452
00:30:24,324 --> 00:30:27,160
You look like a lovely girl.

453
00:30:31,331 --> 00:30:33,416
Let me ask you....

454
00:30:34,542 --> 00:30:40,715
Are you one of these talkers, or would
you be interested in a little action?

455
00:30:40,965 --> 00:30:45,136
-What?
-I got a yen for you right off.

456
00:30:45,387 --> 00:30:49,015
-Well, do you get many?
-Now and then.

457
00:30:49,224 --> 00:30:52,560
-What do you do about it?
-You'll find out.

458
00:30:52,769 --> 00:30:56,815
-I will.
-Want a tip? Sweet-talk me, I like it.

459
00:30:57,065 --> 00:31:02,028
Like that '' lovely girI'' line.
Don't worry, he don't see a thing.

460
00:31:02,278 --> 00:31:05,156
He's too dizzy from being a big man.

461
00:31:05,365 --> 00:31:08,201
This is gonna be different
than I thought.

462
00:31:08,410 --> 00:31:10,620
-Do you mind?
-No.

463
00:31:10,829 --> 00:31:14,708
It's only fair.
We'll educate each other.

464
00:31:15,959 --> 00:31:17,711
-About those books.
-Yes?

465
00:31:18,044 --> 00:31:23,216
I'll look around. lf there's anything
interesting, I'll drop it back.

466
00:31:23,425 --> 00:31:27,637
You can drop it back even
if it's not so interesting.

467
00:31:32,100 --> 00:31:36,604
-You two gonna get together?
-I think we're all set.

468
00:31:36,813 --> 00:31:41,359
-Great, great. Appreciate it.
-So do l.

