510
00:39:39,796 --> 00:39:41,423
How do you know?

511
00:39:41,631 --> 00:39:45,844
lf you're gonna turn out
to be a pest, we can call it off.

512
00:39:46,052 --> 00:39:47,095
Sorry.

513
00:39:47,345 --> 00:39:51,850
I look at the papers sometimes,
but I never understand it.

514
00:39:52,058 --> 00:39:53,935
So what's the sense?

515
00:39:54,144 --> 00:39:58,189
Look through these, and anything
you don't understand...

516
00:39:58,398 --> 00:40:01,735
...make a circle around it.
Then I'll explain.

517
00:40:01,985 --> 00:40:04,571
-Whatever I can. All right?
-All right.

518
00:40:04,779 --> 00:40:08,116
And I thought you might like these.

519
00:40:08,658 --> 00:40:10,660
Well, I'll try.

520
00:40:11,911 --> 00:40:16,249
Start reading. lf you don't
like it, start something else.

521
00:40:16,458 --> 00:40:19,169
One thing, my eyesight isn't so hot.

522
00:40:19,377 --> 00:40:21,546
Why don't you wear glasses?

523
00:40:21,755 --> 00:40:24,632
-Sure, why not?
-Because it's terrible.

524
00:40:40,857 --> 00:40:44,110
Of course, they're not so bad on men.

525
00:40:46,905 --> 00:40:50,283
-Good night, Billie.
-Good night.

526
00:41:10,220 --> 00:41:11,763
Hello!

527
00:41:15,266 --> 00:41:16,976
Miss Dawn around?

528
00:41:19,020 --> 00:41:22,399
-Have you seen Miss Dawn?
-In her room.

529
00:41:26,820 --> 00:41:29,030
-Hello?
-Yes?

530
00:41:29,239 --> 00:41:32,158
-Ready to start.
-Come on up!

531
00:42:03,523 --> 00:42:07,444
-Hello.
-Hello.

532
00:42:10,822 --> 00:42:14,451
-Been reading, huh? That's good.
-Yeah.

533
00:42:14,701 --> 00:42:17,454
-Sit down.
-Thanks.

534
00:42:26,046 --> 00:42:29,549
-Did you have your breakfast yet?
-And lunch.

535
00:42:32,093 --> 00:42:36,014
-There's a few things here.
-Which?

536
00:42:51,112 --> 00:42:52,906
Read it out.

537
00:42:53,990 --> 00:42:56,034
You want me to read?

538
00:42:56,951 --> 00:42:59,829
Billie, things
are complicated enough...

539
00:43:00,038 --> 00:43:03,333
...without complicating them further.

540
00:43:05,377 --> 00:43:09,589
I ought to take this pencil
and make a circle around you.

541
00:43:14,094 --> 00:43:16,471
-Here are a few places you should see.
-A few?

542
00:43:16,680 --> 00:43:21,476
The Capitol. I'll tell you all I know,
then we'll join a tour.

543
00:43:21,685 --> 00:43:24,396
Senate's in session today.

544
00:43:24,646 --> 00:43:28,149
Let's go to the rotunda.
It's famous for its--

545
00:43:28,608 --> 00:43:32,654
-Come on. You'll find it interesting.
-I'm coming.

546
00:43:32,987 --> 00:43:34,656
--now before Congress.

547
00:43:34,906 --> 00:43:40,036
On the walls of this rotunda
are eight historical paintings....

548
00:43:41,955 --> 00:43:45,291
--with the landing of the Pilgrims....

549
00:43:45,500 --> 00:43:49,129
--Revolutionary War paintings,
depicting the start...

550
00:43:49,337 --> 00:43:53,633
...and finish of that war,
and its two greatest battles.

551
00:43:53,842 --> 00:43:59,973
The east wall contains paintings
predating the Revolutionary period.

552
00:44:00,223 --> 00:44:04,269
<i>--The GlOrificatiOn</i>
<i>Of the Spirit Of GeOrge WashingtOn.</i>

553
00:44:04,477 --> 00:44:08,857
Washington is the figure
with the purple robe on his lap.

554
00:44:09,065 --> 00:44:14,154
The figures around him
represent Liberty and Victory.

555
00:44:14,362 --> 00:44:19,284
Brumidi did most of that work
lying on his back...

556
00:44:19,534 --> 00:44:23,580
...on a scaffold built
from the floor to the dome...

557
00:44:23,788 --> 00:44:27,917
...a distance of 1 80 feet
and 3 inches.

558
00:44:29,085 --> 00:44:31,171
Now if you'll follow me....

559
00:44:31,421 --> 00:44:35,091
How could anybody paint
upside down like that?

560
00:44:35,300 --> 00:44:38,219
Hey, give me one of those.

561
00:44:51,149 --> 00:44:53,026
-Hello.
-How are you?

562
00:45:48,790 --> 00:45:51,626
Come here.
I wanna show you something.

563
00:45:57,966 --> 00:46:00,051
There's the Constitution...

564
00:46:01,720 --> 00:46:06,016
...the Declaration of lndependence.
And come here.

565
00:46:10,186 --> 00:46:13,565
And the Bill of Rights.
Know how old these are?

566
00:46:13,815 --> 00:46:17,318
-Oh, about 1 60 years.
-Who told you?

567
00:46:17,569 --> 00:46:21,031
-What else do you know about it?
-What else?

568
00:46:22,657 --> 00:46:25,410
-What else?
-This whole country...

569
00:46:25,618 --> 00:46:29,581
...is founded on these
three pieces of paper.

570
00:46:29,789 --> 00:46:32,292
This whole country?

571
00:46:36,254 --> 00:46:41,092
''The right of the people
to keep and bear arms...

572
00:46:41,343 --> 00:46:45,221
-...shall not be in-fringed.''
-lnfringed.

573
00:46:45,889 --> 00:46:51,353
Good thing it's covered with glass.
I'd be making circles all over it.

574
00:46:52,562 --> 00:46:54,397
How about some ice cream?

575
00:46:56,274 --> 00:46:58,985
Anything but tutti-frutti.

576
00:47:00,737 --> 00:47:02,572
-How's chocolate?
-Fine.

577
00:47:02,781 --> 00:47:06,117
-I like you better with them on.
-What?

578
00:47:06,326 --> 00:47:08,370
Your glasses!

579
00:47:12,832 --> 00:47:16,461
Thanks. You know, chocolate's
the most popular.

580
00:47:16,670 --> 00:47:18,171
I read that.

581
00:47:18,963 --> 00:47:24,010
It's interesting how many things
a person could learn if they read.

582
00:47:24,636 --> 00:47:27,180
I don't suppose you read my piece.

583
00:47:27,430 --> 00:47:30,892
What are you talking?
Of course I read it. Twice.

584
00:47:31,101 --> 00:47:32,811
What did you think?

585
00:47:33,061 --> 00:47:38,108
It's the best thing I ever read.
I didn't understand one word.

586
00:47:39,109 --> 00:47:42,987
-What didn't you understand?
-None of it.

587
00:47:44,322 --> 00:47:46,533
Here. Show me what.

588
00:47:55,959 --> 00:47:59,713
What's so funny?
That I'm blind, practically?

589
00:48:00,130 --> 00:48:01,756
Practically blind.

590
00:48:01,965 --> 00:48:04,426
-Practically blind?
-You're wonderful.

591
00:48:04,634 --> 00:48:08,888
-I'm sorry I look funny to you.
-You look lovelier than ever.

592
00:48:09,097 --> 00:48:12,642
You sound like one of those
ads for eyeglasses.

593
00:48:12,892 --> 00:48:14,978
What didn't you understand?

594
00:48:15,186 --> 00:48:19,733
Well, like the name of it:
''The Yellowing Democratic Manifesto.''

595
00:48:19,941 --> 00:48:24,070
-Simple.
-To who? Whom? Who?

596
00:48:24,571 --> 00:48:26,364
Well, anyway, not to me.

597
00:48:26,573 --> 00:48:29,951
-You know what ''yellowing'' means.
-Not this time.

598
00:48:30,160 --> 00:48:33,621
When a piece of paper gets old,
what happens to it?

599
00:48:34,039 --> 00:48:37,000
-Throw it away?
-No, it turns yellow.

600
00:48:37,208 --> 00:48:38,918
-It does?
-Of course.

601
00:48:39,127 --> 00:48:41,046
What do you know?

602
00:48:41,254 --> 00:48:45,216
-You know what '' Democratic'' means.
-Not Republican.

603
00:48:46,676 --> 00:48:48,970
Well, not exactly.

604
00:48:49,220 --> 00:48:53,933
It means pertaining to our form
of government, which is a democracy.

605
00:48:54,476 --> 00:48:58,104
-What's pertaining?
-'' Has to do with.''

606
00:48:58,355 --> 00:49:00,732
Pertaining. Nice word.

607
00:49:00,940 --> 00:49:03,735
-All right. '' Manifesto.''
-I don't know.

608
00:49:03,985 --> 00:49:07,572
-Why didn't you look it up?
-I did. I still don't know.

609
00:49:08,114 --> 00:49:12,660
By ''manifesto'' I mean the rules,
principles, ideals and hopes...

610
00:49:12,869 --> 00:49:15,580
...on which the United States is based.

611
00:49:15,789 --> 00:49:19,209
The ideas of the men who
wrote the Constitution.

612
00:49:19,417 --> 00:49:22,128
-You think it's turning yellow?
-Yes.

613
00:49:22,337 --> 00:49:25,674
The original inspiration
has been forgotten.

614
00:49:25,882 --> 00:49:28,760
-And that's bad?
-And that's bad.

615
00:49:32,305 --> 00:49:33,723
'' Even a--''

616
00:49:34,015 --> 00:49:35,767
-'' Cursory''?
-Cursory.

617
00:49:35,975 --> 00:49:39,229
''--examination of contemporary...

618
00:49:39,479 --> 00:49:42,148
...society in terms of the Greek...

619
00:49:42,357 --> 00:49:46,277
...philosophy, which defines
the whole as a representation...

620
00:49:46,486 --> 00:49:49,406
...of its parts,
sends one immediately...

621
00:49:49,656 --> 00:49:53,576
...to the consideration of
the individual as a citizen...

622
00:49:53,827 --> 00:49:56,830
...and the citizen as an individual.''

623
00:49:57,038 --> 00:50:01,334
-Well?
-I looked up every word.

624
00:50:03,503 --> 00:50:05,005
Listen.

625
00:50:05,213 --> 00:50:08,758
Thousands of years ago,
a Greek philosopher said...

626
00:50:08,967 --> 00:50:12,429
...the world could only be
as good as its inhabitants.

627
00:50:12,637 --> 00:50:14,431
-Makes sense.
-So I said...

628
00:50:14,681 --> 00:50:16,516
...take one look at America...

629
00:50:16,766 --> 00:50:21,229
...and you figure you better look
at the people in it. One by one.

630
00:50:21,438 --> 00:50:22,981
That's all.

631
00:50:23,523 --> 00:50:26,109
-That's this?
-Sure.

632
00:50:26,317 --> 00:50:29,029
Well, why didn't you say so?

633
00:51:15,700 --> 00:51:21,581
-What's the name of this number?
-Beethoven's Second Symphony, Opus 36.

634
00:51:21,790 --> 00:51:26,127
I didn't ask you who made it up.
I just asked the name of it.

635
00:51:44,521 --> 00:51:46,606
Here. Wait a minute.

636
00:51:51,027 --> 00:51:53,279
-There.
-Thanks.

637
00:51:56,658 --> 00:51:59,911
-I can't get over it.
-Music that bad?

638
00:52:00,370 --> 00:52:04,749
-The music? Oh, it was swell.
-Well then, what?

639
00:52:05,166 --> 00:52:07,877
I got a letter today, from my father.

640
00:52:08,086 --> 00:52:09,421
-New York?
-Yeah.

641
00:52:09,671 --> 00:52:12,132
-I can't get over it.
-Why?

642
00:52:12,340 --> 00:52:16,094
It's the first time he wrote me
in about eight years.

643
00:52:16,344 --> 00:52:21,850
We had a fight, sort of.
He didn't want me to go with Harry.

644
00:52:22,058 --> 00:52:23,393
What does he do?

645
00:52:23,643 --> 00:52:25,186
-My father?
-Yeah.

646
00:52:25,395 --> 00:52:27,772
Gas company. He read metres...

647
00:52:28,023 --> 00:52:31,443
...but he can't get around
so good anymore...

648
00:52:31,651 --> 00:52:35,613
...so they gave him a different job.
Elevator man.

649
00:52:36,156 --> 00:52:39,659
He's a goofy old guy.
He used to take a frying pan...

650
00:52:39,868 --> 00:52:43,163
...to work every day
and cook his lunch.

651
00:52:43,413 --> 00:52:46,875
He said everybody
should have a hot lunch.

652
00:52:47,792 --> 00:52:49,878
I don't know how he did it.

653
00:52:50,086 --> 00:52:53,757
Four of us. Me and my three brothers.
He did everything.

654
00:52:53,965 --> 00:52:56,676
My mother died. I never knew her.

655
00:52:56,885 --> 00:53:01,348
He used to feed us and give us
our bath and buy our clothes.

656
00:53:01,598 --> 00:53:03,350
Everything.

657
00:53:04,434 --> 00:53:09,731
All my life I used to think how
someday I'd like to pay him back.

658
00:53:13,276 --> 00:53:16,071
It's funny how it worked out.

659
00:53:16,988 --> 00:53:22,535
Once I brought home $1 00 and gave it
to him. You know what he did?

660
00:53:25,372 --> 00:53:28,708
Well, it sure didn't
do the plumbing no good.

661
00:53:28,917 --> 00:53:34,839
I thought he'd hit me, but he didn't.
His whole life, he never hit me once.

662
00:53:35,757 --> 00:53:39,344
How'd he happen to write you,
after all this time?

663
00:53:39,552 --> 00:53:41,721
Because I wrote him.

664
00:53:42,180 --> 00:53:45,475
He says he's thought about me
every day.

665
00:53:46,226 --> 00:53:48,186
Gosh!

666
00:53:48,853 --> 00:53:54,651
I haven't thought about him,
I bet once even, in five years.

667
00:53:55,694 --> 00:54:00,365
Oh, that's nothing against him.
I haven't thought of anything.

668
00:54:00,824 --> 00:54:02,992
Be nice to see him, maybe.

669
00:54:03,535 --> 00:54:05,328
I guess so.

670
00:54:05,578 --> 00:54:10,709
He says I should write again, and
I should have a hot lunch every day.

671
00:54:10,917 --> 00:54:13,503
And I should let him know how I am.

672
00:54:13,753 --> 00:54:18,258
But he won't see me if I'm still
living in any way unethical.

673
00:54:18,466 --> 00:54:20,510
I looked it up.

674
00:54:20,760 --> 00:54:23,638
He always said, '' Never do nothing...

675
00:54:23,847 --> 00:54:27,809
...you wouldn't want printed
in the <i>New YOrk Times. ''</i>

676
00:54:29,978 --> 00:54:34,691
I practically told you the whole
story of my life by now.

677
00:54:35,191 --> 00:54:37,444
I enjoyed it very much.

678
00:54:37,777 --> 00:54:41,573
-How about the story of your life?
-Oh, no.

679
00:54:41,781 --> 00:54:43,867
Much too long...

680
00:54:44,826 --> 00:54:46,995
...and mostly untrue.

681
00:55:18,401 --> 00:55:23,406
This is even more gorgeous than
the Radio City Music Hall, even.

682
00:55:23,615 --> 00:55:26,618
And do you notice? It smells nice.

683
00:55:26,826 --> 00:55:28,536
It does!

684
00:55:33,750 --> 00:55:35,627
-Come on. Sit down.
-No.

685
00:55:35,835 --> 00:55:37,671
You're tired.

686
00:55:39,047 --> 00:55:41,633
I'm not a bit tired.

687
00:55:44,594 --> 00:55:45,845
See?

688
00:55:46,054 --> 00:55:49,057
You know the thing you gave me
about Napoleon?

689
00:55:49,265 --> 00:55:51,309
-What?
-By Robert G. lngersoll?

690
00:55:51,559 --> 00:55:53,895
-Oh, yes.
-I'm not sure I get it.

691
00:55:54,104 --> 00:55:56,981
-There's no deep meaning.
-There must be.

692
00:55:57,190 --> 00:56:00,276
He goes and looks in Napoleon's tomb...

693
00:56:00,485 --> 00:56:03,446
...and he thinks
of Napoleon's sad life.

694
00:56:03,655 --> 00:56:08,493
And then he says he himself
would have rather been a happy farmer.

695
00:56:08,702 --> 00:56:14,791
'' I would rather have been a French
peasant, and worn wooden shoes.

696
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:19,879
I would rather have lived in a hut
with a vine growing over the door.

697
00:56:20,130 --> 00:56:24,384
And the grapes growing purple
in the kisses of the autumn sun.

698
00:56:25,218 --> 00:56:30,181
I would rather have been a poor
peasant, with my wife by my side...

699
00:56:30,390 --> 00:56:33,560
...knitting as the day
died out of the sky...

700
00:56:33,768 --> 00:56:38,148
...with my children upon my knee
and their arms about me.

701
00:56:38,648 --> 00:56:41,443
I would rather have been that man...

702
00:56:41,651 --> 00:56:46,072
...and gone down to the tongueless
silence of the dreamless dust...

703
00:56:46,281 --> 00:56:50,702
...than to have been that imperial
impersonation of force and murder...

704
00:56:50,952 --> 00:56:53,580
...known as Napoleon the Great.''

705
00:56:55,540 --> 00:56:59,002
How do you remember
all that stuff?

706
00:57:05,008 --> 00:57:09,304
So he'd rather be a happy peasant
than Napoleon. Who wouldn't?

707
00:57:09,512 --> 00:57:11,639
Harry wouldn't, for one.

708
00:57:11,848 --> 00:57:14,851
-What makes you think that?
-Ask him.

709
00:57:15,060 --> 00:57:17,645
He probably never heard
of Napoleon.

710
00:57:17,896 --> 00:57:21,733
What's worse, he probably never
heard of a peasant.

711
00:57:23,193 --> 00:57:25,153
Do you hate him like poison?

712
00:57:25,403 --> 00:57:27,030
-Who? Harry?
-Yeah.

713
00:57:27,280 --> 00:57:29,032
-No.
-You don't like him.

714
00:57:29,240 --> 00:57:30,492
No.

715
00:57:30,742 --> 00:57:34,371
-On account of me and him?
-One reason. There are lots more.

716
00:57:34,579 --> 00:57:38,124
-What?
-Think about it. Harry's a menace.

717
00:57:38,333 --> 00:57:40,794
He's not so bad. I seen worse.

718
00:57:41,002 --> 00:57:43,880
Has he ever thought of anyone
but himself?

719
00:57:44,089 --> 00:57:45,507
Who does?

720
00:57:45,715 --> 00:57:49,135
History is the story
of the struggle between...

721
00:57:49,344 --> 00:57:52,847
-...the selfish and the unselfish.
-I can hear you.

722
00:57:53,098 --> 00:57:55,975
All that's bad is bred by selfishness.

723
00:57:56,184 --> 00:58:00,730
Sometimes selfishness can get to be
a cause, an organized force.

724
00:58:00,939 --> 00:58:04,192
Even a government.
Then it's called fascism.

725
00:58:04,484 --> 00:58:07,696
-Can you understand that?
-Sort of.

726
00:58:07,904 --> 00:58:12,534
-Well, think about it.
-You're crazy about me, aren't you?

727
00:58:12,742 --> 00:58:16,079
-Yes.
-That's why you get so mad at Harry.

728
00:58:16,663 --> 00:58:21,209
I hate his life, what he does,
what he stands for. Not him.

729
00:58:21,459 --> 00:58:26,589
-He just doesn't know any better.
-I go for you too.

730
00:58:27,799 --> 00:58:29,926
I'm glad of it.

731
00:58:45,066 --> 00:58:48,611
'' I've sworn upon the altar of God...

732
00:58:48,820 --> 00:58:53,950
...eternal hostility against
every form of tyranny...

733
00:58:54,993 --> 00:58:57,454
...over the mind of man.''

734
00:59:00,081 --> 00:59:03,335
So that's Thomas Jefferson, huh?

735
00:59:03,543 --> 00:59:05,920
I heard quite a bit about him.

736
00:59:06,129 --> 00:59:09,341
I mean even before
I hit town, even.

737
00:59:20,560 --> 00:59:22,062
Come in.

738
00:59:27,692 --> 00:59:30,779
What are you trying to do
with those books, hatch them?

739
00:59:32,822 --> 00:59:33,948
Blue?

740
00:59:36,451 --> 00:59:37,911
Nice, that.

741
00:59:38,870 --> 00:59:41,873
Beethoven. Op 36.

742
00:59:43,708 --> 00:59:47,712
-What's up?
-It's because of you I'm doing this.

743
00:59:47,962 --> 00:59:50,215
-I guess you know.
-No, I didn't.

744
00:59:50,799 --> 00:59:55,845
A lot of good it did me.
I never had this trouble before.

745
00:59:56,513 --> 00:59:58,932
-Trouble?
-Sure.

746
00:59:59,140 --> 01:00:03,520
When I met you, I figured everything
is gonna work out dandy.

747
01:00:03,728 --> 01:00:07,357
Then when you wouldn't
step across the line...

748
01:00:07,607 --> 01:00:11,361
...I figured maybe the way
to you is through your head.

749
01:00:12,487 --> 01:00:13,988
Well, no.

750
01:00:15,907 --> 01:00:19,411
Well, anyway, what's the diff now?
Difference.

751
01:00:19,661 --> 01:00:23,498
But I like you anyway.
It's too late for the rest.

752
01:00:23,707 --> 01:00:26,543
-Why?
-Why?

753
01:00:26,793 --> 01:00:30,505
There's a certain time
between a fellow and a girl...

754
01:00:30,755 --> 01:00:35,385
...when it either comes off or not.
lf it doesn't then, it never does.

755
01:00:35,593 --> 01:00:41,474
-Maybe we haven't got to our time yet.
-I think so. You dropped the ball.

756
01:00:41,683 --> 01:00:43,309
Don't be so sure.

757
01:00:44,019 --> 01:00:47,480
I never thought I'd
go through a thing like this.

758
01:00:47,689 --> 01:00:50,859
-Like what?
-Like getting all mixed-up.

759
01:00:51,067 --> 01:00:55,321
Like wondering and worrying
and thinking. Stuff like that.

760
01:00:55,530 --> 01:01:00,660
Last night I started thinking.
I couldn't fall asleep for 1 0 minutes!

761
01:01:00,952 --> 01:01:04,831
I don't know if it's good
to find out so much so quick.

762
01:01:05,040 --> 01:01:10,003
Nobody's born smart. Know what
the stupidest thing on earth is? A baby.

763
01:01:10,211 --> 01:01:12,380
What have you got against babies?

764
01:01:12,630 --> 01:01:16,718
I've got nothing against a brain
that's three weeks old.

765
01:01:16,926 --> 01:01:20,680
But if it's still empty after
30 years, I begin to wonder.

766
01:01:20,889 --> 01:01:23,433
-Who says I'm 30?
-I didn't--

767
01:01:23,641 --> 01:01:25,018
-You did!
-I swear.

768
01:01:25,226 --> 01:01:27,645
-You sure can get me sore.
-Sorry.

769
01:01:27,854 --> 01:01:29,856
-Do I look 30 to you?
-No.

770
01:01:30,065 --> 01:01:32,859
-Then why'd you say it?
-I don't know.

771
01:01:33,068 --> 01:01:35,945
-How old are you?
-Twenty-nine!

772
01:01:40,116 --> 01:01:41,826
Don't stop.

773
01:01:42,035 --> 01:01:44,287
I meant, don't stop studying.

774
01:01:44,871 --> 01:01:46,373
Will you?

775
01:01:47,040 --> 01:01:50,043
I don't know why
it's so important to you.

776
01:01:50,251 --> 01:01:53,213
Sort of a cause.
I want everyone to be smart.

777
01:01:53,421 --> 01:01:55,548
As smart as they can be.

778
01:01:55,799 --> 01:01:58,593
A world of ignorant people
is dangerous.

779
01:01:58,802 --> 01:02:04,224
-That's why I wish I was doing better.
-You're doing wonderfully.

780
01:02:04,432 --> 01:02:08,687
Most people would laugh
if they knew what I was trying....

781
01:02:08,937 --> 01:02:13,608
-I'm not laughing.
-I am. I'm sort of laughing at myself.

782
01:02:13,817 --> 01:02:16,611
Who do I think I am, anyway?

783
01:02:23,368 --> 01:02:25,704
Once in a while, for a change.

784
01:02:25,912 --> 01:02:29,165
Don't try so hard.
You miss the whole point.

785
01:02:29,416 --> 01:02:33,670
-I wanna like what's best to like.
-You have room for a lot.

786
01:02:33,795 --> 01:02:36,131
One learns to be bigger, not smaller.

787
01:02:36,297 --> 01:02:38,550
-I'm getting bigger?
-Yes.

788
01:02:38,800 --> 01:02:40,802
Glad to hear it.

789
01:02:41,136 --> 01:02:43,013
But all them books!

790
01:02:43,221 --> 01:02:45,932
I told you, it's not only books.

791
01:02:46,141 --> 01:02:48,059
-It's mostly.
-It is not.

792
01:02:48,268 --> 01:02:51,604
Who said, ''The proper study
of mankind is man''?

793
01:02:51,813 --> 01:02:53,314
-Who?
-You should know.

794
01:02:53,523 --> 01:02:54,566
-Why?
-I told you.

795
01:02:54,733 --> 01:02:56,026
-I forgot.
-Pope.

796
01:02:56,234 --> 01:02:59,946
-The pope?
-Not ''the pope.'' Alexander Pope.

797
01:03:01,865 --> 01:03:04,617
-''The proper study--''
-''--of mankind is man.''

798
01:03:04,868 --> 01:03:07,954
-Of course, that means women too.
-Yes.

799
01:03:08,204 --> 01:03:09,789
Yes, I know.

800
01:03:10,582 --> 01:03:13,877
I've been studying
different mankind lately.

801
01:03:14,085 --> 01:03:18,757
Like the ones you told me.
Thomas Jefferson and Tom Paine.

802
01:03:19,007 --> 01:03:22,469
And all by myself
I got to thinking about Harry.

803
01:03:22,927 --> 01:03:26,890
He works so hard
to get what he wants, for instance.

804
01:03:27,098 --> 01:03:29,559
But he doesn't know what he wants.

805
01:03:29,768 --> 01:03:32,896
-More of what he's got, probably.
-Money.

806
01:03:33,104 --> 01:03:36,816
Money, more people to push around,
more money.

807
01:03:37,025 --> 01:03:39,903
He's not so bad as you think he is.

808
01:03:41,905 --> 01:03:43,990
We were just talking about you.

809
01:03:44,240 --> 01:03:48,953
That ain't why I pay you.
She knows enough about me. Too much.

810
01:03:49,162 --> 01:03:51,831
Jim phone? I had a date with him.

811
01:03:52,040 --> 01:03:54,668
-What about Paine?
-He was quite a fellow.

812
01:03:54,918 --> 01:03:58,797
-Where was he born?
-London or England. A place like that.

813
01:03:59,005 --> 01:04:02,258
-London or--? It's the same thing.
-It is?

814
01:04:02,467 --> 01:04:06,304
London's a city
in the country of England.

815
01:04:06,513 --> 01:04:08,556
-You got patience.
-Take it easy.

816
01:04:08,765 --> 01:04:12,352
-How can she be so dumb?
-We can't all know everything.

817
01:04:12,602 --> 01:04:15,689
-Who's Tom Paine, for instance?
-What?

818
01:04:15,939 --> 01:04:19,275
-You heard me. Tom Paine.
-What do I care?

819
01:04:19,484 --> 01:04:20,527
I know.

820
01:04:20,735 --> 01:04:24,656
lf I wanted to know who he is,
I'd know. I don't care.

821
01:04:24,864 --> 01:04:28,159
-Don't let me butt in.
-Which book did you like?

822
01:04:28,368 --> 01:04:31,996
I didn't read by him.
Only about him. I made a list.

823
01:04:32,247 --> 01:04:34,666
-Who's '' Rabbit'' Maranville?
-Who?

824
01:04:34,874 --> 01:04:37,711
-'' Rabbit'' Maranville.
-I don't know rabbits.

825
01:04:37,919 --> 01:04:41,965
-Think you're smart, huh?
-He was shortstop for the Braves.

826
01:04:42,215 --> 01:04:45,010
-What are you? Some kind of genius?
-No.

827
01:04:45,218 --> 01:04:48,263
-I hire and fire geniuses every day.
-I'm sure.

828
01:04:48,471 --> 01:04:50,265
-Where's the list?
-Here.

829
01:04:50,473 --> 01:04:53,643
Suppose you start
with <i>The Age Of ReasOn.</i>

830
01:04:53,893 --> 01:04:56,187
<i>-The Age Of ReasOn</i>?
-Then, next--

831
01:04:56,396 --> 01:04:59,107
-Who's Willie Hop?
-Billiard champion.

832
01:04:59,357 --> 01:05:02,193
-It's pronounced '' Hoppe.''
-I asked her.

833
01:05:02,402 --> 01:05:05,530
-Sorry. Where were we?
<i>-The Age Of ReasOn.</i>

834
01:05:05,780 --> 01:05:09,117
-Yes. Next, <i>The Rights Of Man.</i>
<i>-The Rights Of Man.</i>

835
01:05:09,367 --> 01:05:11,578
-I think--
-What's a peninsula?

836
01:05:11,828 --> 01:05:14,914
You think you're so smart?
What's a peninsula?

837
01:05:15,165 --> 01:05:19,252
-Not you. Her.
-It's that new medicine.

838
01:05:21,546 --> 01:05:23,048
It is not.

839
01:05:23,965 --> 01:05:26,134
-What then?
-A body of land...

840
01:05:26,343 --> 01:05:28,845
...surrounded on three sides
by water.

841
01:05:29,054 --> 01:05:32,015
-So what?
-So what about Sam Paine?

842
01:05:32,223 --> 01:05:35,894
Some difference between--
Tom Paine! Not Sam Paine!

843
01:05:36,102 --> 01:05:40,357
Tom Paine practically started
this whole country.

844
01:05:41,191 --> 01:05:43,318
-You mean he's dead?
-Of course.

845
01:05:43,568 --> 01:05:47,364
I want you to learn her how to act
with live people.

846
01:05:47,572 --> 01:05:50,325
Education's difficult to control--

847
01:05:50,533 --> 01:05:52,660
-Work on her.
-No extra charge.

848
01:05:52,869 --> 01:05:56,122
-I don't need nothing you can tell me.
-We could...

849
01:05:56,331 --> 01:05:59,167
...tell each other some
interesting things.

850
01:05:59,376 --> 01:06:01,628
-What's the idea?
-Being friendly.

851
01:06:01,836 --> 01:06:03,254
Who asked you?

852
01:06:03,630 --> 01:06:06,341
The more I see you
I don't like you as much.

853
01:06:06,549 --> 01:06:08,510
You're awful fresh.

854
01:06:08,760 --> 01:06:12,889
-Watch out. I got my eye on you.
-Okay. We'll both watch out.

855
01:06:13,139 --> 01:06:16,559
-I could knock your block off.
-Yes, I know.

856
01:06:16,768 --> 01:06:20,146
Just do what you're supposed
to do, that's all.

857
01:06:20,355 --> 01:06:21,606
We'll stop now.

858
01:06:21,815 --> 01:06:25,110
-Go on. I wanna see how you do it.
-Not now.

859
01:06:25,318 --> 01:06:28,947
I've gotta lie down.
You don't realize how hard I work.

860
01:06:29,155 --> 01:06:30,407
Some joke!

861
01:06:30,657 --> 01:06:35,578
-200 bucks a week and I can't watch.
-Take you on separately. Glad to.

862
01:06:35,787 --> 01:06:39,374
Got a special course
for backward millionaires.

863
01:06:45,255 --> 01:06:50,427
'' London or England.''
Why don't you give up?

864
01:07:01,396 --> 01:07:03,732
-Harry?
-What?

865
01:07:04,399 --> 01:07:08,528
What's this business we're in
down here? Could you tell me?

866
01:07:08,737 --> 01:07:10,405
What do you mean, ''we''?

867
01:07:10,613 --> 01:07:14,409
-I figure I'm a partner, in a way.
-A silent partner.

868
01:07:14,659 --> 01:07:17,120
-So?
-So shut up.

869
01:07:18,747 --> 01:07:20,498
I got a right to know.

870
01:07:20,707 --> 01:07:23,793
Keep out of my hair.
Put your nose in a book.

871
01:07:24,002 --> 01:07:27,172
I don't want to do anything
against the law.

872
01:07:27,380 --> 01:07:28,923
Do what I tell you.

873
01:07:29,132 --> 01:07:32,135
I think I know what it is,
only I'm not sure.

874
01:07:32,344 --> 01:07:34,888
What's the matter?
You do all right.

875
01:07:35,138 --> 01:07:37,807
Something you want
you ain't got, maybe?

876
01:07:38,725 --> 01:07:44,022
-What?
-I wanna be like the happy peasant.

877
01:07:45,023 --> 01:07:49,569
All right, I'll buy it for you.
Now will you quit crabbing?

878
01:07:50,320 --> 01:07:53,615
I finished finally.
Thanks loads for the loan.

879
01:07:53,823 --> 01:07:56,117
-How'd you like it?
-Oh, not me.

880
01:07:56,326 --> 01:08:00,413
I don't like when everyone
has a beef against the world.

881
01:08:00,622 --> 01:08:04,501
-I like to look on the cheerful side.
-Well, the point--

882
01:08:04,751 --> 01:08:10,256
-Can the coffee klatch. You, knock off.
-Sorry, Mr. Brock.

883
01:08:11,216 --> 01:08:14,052
-Don't get so pally.
-Paul says it's okay.

884
01:08:14,302 --> 01:08:17,806
-Never mind him. I don't like it.
-Know what you are?

885
01:08:18,014 --> 01:08:19,265
What?

886
01:08:28,525 --> 01:08:31,861
-Antisocial!
-You can say that again.

887
01:08:32,779 --> 01:08:34,531
Where you guys been?

888
01:08:34,781 --> 01:08:36,533
-Sorry.
-You're always sorry.

889
01:08:36,741 --> 01:08:39,744
-My fault. How do you do?
-How do you do?

890
01:08:39,953 --> 01:08:44,457
-How are you, Billie?
-Superb. A new word.

891
01:08:45,375 --> 01:08:49,087
-All right, what happened?
-It may take more time--

892
01:08:49,295 --> 01:08:51,047
-And more money.
-Why more?

893
01:08:51,256 --> 01:08:54,259
The amendment has to be redrafted.

894
01:08:56,511 --> 01:09:00,974
-You make me feel like a sucker.
-NorvaI's doing his best.

895
01:09:01,182 --> 01:09:04,728
-It ain't good enough.
-There are a lot of votes.

896
01:09:04,936 --> 01:09:07,856
-NorvaI's just one guy.
-He's the wrong guy.

897
01:09:09,482 --> 01:09:11,317
I'm sick of waiting.

898
01:09:11,526 --> 01:09:16,197
Pull your weight in this deal
or I'll get somebody who can.

899
01:09:17,824 --> 01:09:19,367
Quite a temper.

900
01:09:19,617 --> 01:09:25,373
Don't mind him. He's always lived
at the top of his voice. So long, Norval.

901
01:09:39,387 --> 01:09:43,767
Harry shouldn't talk to you like that.
You're a congressman.

902
01:09:44,017 --> 01:09:45,268
Oh, well.

903
01:09:45,477 --> 01:09:50,148
No one should talk to a congressman
like that, or be able to.

904
01:09:50,648 --> 01:09:54,778
-Being a congressman is wonderful.
-Thank you.

905
01:09:55,028 --> 01:09:57,489
I think I could use a drink.

906
01:09:57,697 --> 01:10:01,201
Oh, sure, congressman. Come on in.

907
01:10:02,118 --> 01:10:06,915
lf he pushes you around, he's
pushing a few million people around.

908
01:10:07,248 --> 01:10:09,417
-Who?
-The ones who picked you.

909
01:10:09,668 --> 01:10:12,045
-Not quite that many.
-How many?

910
01:10:12,253 --> 01:10:15,465
306,434.

911
01:10:15,715 --> 01:10:18,760
That's quite a few to push around.

912
01:10:18,968 --> 01:10:23,556
You're not one of my constituents
by any chance, are you?

913
01:10:30,730 --> 01:10:35,360
-One of the people who voted for me?
-Oh, I never voted for anybody.

914
01:10:35,568 --> 01:10:37,904
-Why not?
-I wouldn't know how.

915
01:10:38,113 --> 01:10:42,117
-Simple. You just press a button.
-Yeah. But which one?

916
01:10:42,325 --> 01:10:47,956
You listen to the speeches.
You make up your own mind. That's all.

917
01:10:48,164 --> 01:10:50,458
Why do you take it from Harry?

918
01:10:50,667 --> 01:10:54,838
You're more important than him.
You're a congressman.

919
01:10:55,046 --> 01:10:58,383
Yes, and as such,
I have a great many duties...

920
01:10:58,633 --> 01:11:01,469
...and responsibilities and....

921
01:11:01,761 --> 01:11:05,056
The operation of government
is very complex.

922
01:11:05,306 --> 01:11:10,228
Why should it be? I understand it in
the books, and when Paul tells me.

923
01:11:10,437 --> 01:11:13,732
But when I see this
happen, it's different.

924
01:11:13,940 --> 01:11:15,191
How?

925
01:11:15,400 --> 01:11:20,113
When it's a matter of the law,
is Harry more important than others?

926
01:11:20,280 --> 01:11:21,322
No.

927
01:11:21,448 --> 01:11:26,327
Then how come he's got so much to say?
Who ever voted for him?

928
01:11:30,165 --> 01:11:34,461
Well, we'll have a nice,
long talk about it sometime.

929
01:11:36,254 --> 01:11:38,006
All right.

930
01:11:38,256 --> 01:11:40,550
-Goodbye.
-Goodbye.

931
01:11:40,759 --> 01:11:42,594
And thank you.

932
01:11:52,187 --> 01:11:54,272
Quite a little girl.

933
01:11:56,775 --> 01:11:58,401
-Billie?
-Come in.

934
01:11:58,610 --> 01:12:02,822
Will you come inside?
A few things for you.

935
01:12:12,374 --> 01:12:14,918
Sign those, will you, honey?

936
01:12:17,671 --> 01:12:20,298
-What is this?
-Same old stuff.

937
01:12:20,507 --> 01:12:24,094
-What?
-Take too long to explain.

938
01:12:24,344 --> 01:12:28,932
I like having things explained
to me. I found that out.

939
01:12:29,182 --> 01:12:32,018
-Some other time.
-Now.

940
01:12:32,227 --> 01:12:36,606
-It's an agreement about a merger.
-Merger?

941
